I keep telling myself she's getting bad legal advice.  Sure, she's got
something valuable to protect, but this contrasts greatly with the IP
commentary many people see in her discussion of goblin made armor and
swords.  We are not renting our books, once they are published, they
are no longer hers.  She gets royalties, not rent.  She is still the
author, but, she no longer is the sole possessor the the product she
made.  The fundamental truth of the business of ideas is that ideas
improve when they go public.  This is because readers aren't simply
consumers of ideas, they are the building blocks that more ideas come
from.  This is easier to see in the sciences, technology, and even
legal professions.  What would lawyers do without their precedents?
That is why so many of these bad IP ideas migrate in from the
entertainment industry where the naive see no problem in having one
individual control a whole raft of popular culture.  The ironic thing,
actually, another ironic thing, the Rowling as Goblin was the first,
is that Rowling borrows so much from previous authors such as Tolkein
and Malory.
