It also occurs to me that JKR, or more likely her lawyers, have
concluded that allowing any non-JKR person to write more HP material
will lead to a loss of control over the product.

One idiot could put crazy ideas into their work, call it a part of her
universe, and splatter her with the Dungbomb he'd set off.  It could be
ideas diametrically opposed to hers, or ideas that are towards her end
of the spectrum, but taken to an extreme that she does not agree with.

The only real way to prevent this is to be very assertive in the realm
of artistic control, and as much as we may not like it, it does mean
coming down like a heap of anvils on the people who toe the line too much.

Part of the problem is the tendency of some people to regard the truth
as always existing between the two opposing viewpoints, and failing to
recognize that sometimes, yes, the one party is 100% right and the other
guy is 100% wrong; as a response, people are so accustomed to being
forced into a compromise (one that robs them of what is legitimately
theirs), and so in order to actually keep what's rightfully theirs (or
get it back), they have to overstate their case.

Hence the current legal climate.

Regards,
John
